Q65: I feel that for the most part, students at Bowdoin are very intellectually engaged, and I sincerely appreciate how frequently academic discussions transcend the classroom space. However, I also feel as though there are many students here who do not contriute as much as they could (should?) to this intellectual climate. It is an absolute privilege to be at a school that cultivates meaningful learning as does Bowdoin, and it upsets me how frequently students here undermine the academic system in favor of oter pursuits that do not seem as demonstrative of a meaningful and well-lived four years. I obviously have no right to pass judgement on these individuals, but it does upset me to think that some do not appreciate how much Bowdoin professors--generally speking--care about their students. Similarly, I am now facing some extreme frustration with myself based on this reality. Despite being an extremely (perhaps too) hardworking student in high school, I didn't realize the full potentiality of this academic exerience until late in my senior year. While this is predominantly a personal issue, I do feel as though Bowdoin could do more to help first years engage in the intellectual climate and discover their passions early on so that years one and two are not ridled with too many introductory courses etc.
Q67: I responded uncomfortable--even though it may be overly harsh--because this question touches on the current existential quandaries that dominate my thoughts. This year, unlike any other, has left me particularly disenchanted by the social scene here. As mch as Bowdoin aims to improve diversity across numerous spectra, I feel as though the college often seems more like a vexed microcosm of neoliberalism's flaws, or at least a space full of intensive divides (many of which are based upon class). One of the ost apparent manifestations of this has to be the somewhat pernicious divide between athletes/close friends of athletes and non-athletes. I understand that the closeness teams experience is primarily due to how much time they spend together, but I also fel like the ensuing disunity antagonizes the community-feel the college envisions. As a non-athlete and thus someone "lower" on the hierarchy, I've felt frustrated with the system less out of envy or longing and more because it's feeling more and more likea continuation of high school drama. I recognize that this is not a reality unique to Bowdoin, but I wish that there were a greater sense of transparency at this institution. Everyone appears happy and contented on the surface, but I know that I am not alne in my general discomforts. As an introvert, I do not mind that I am sometimes displeased with social opportunities (not to say there aren't numerous ways to be involved in the campus in general), but it still upsets me to witness such a divided social cene in a place that strives for cross-cultural learning. I think that more so than people acknowledge, the social scene enables the perpetuation of certain divides that are not very productive.

Q25b:
Taking two projects-based computer science courses this semester showed me the importance and reward of teamwork. I am a very indepedent person, and, as such, I worked alone most of the time in previous semesters and resented the times when I would have t work in groups. However, this semester, I quickly realized that I could not do the work for these classes alone (and the professors suggested that we work in groups anyway). In the interest of self-preservation, I sought to make connections with those whm I thought could help me most. As a "lone wolf," this was very challenging.

I eventually became very close with the people I worked with in these classes, and I much better understand the value of working together: sharing knowledge, building camaradeie, reconciling different perspectives and more. While these experiences are not specific to academics, the fact that I had them in an academic setting made a very strong impression on me because I had not previously recognized how academics could change y perspective on how I work with other people.

Q67: The dominant social culture at Bowdoin is very unhealthy for the students and the school. The only reason I didn't mark my answer as "Very uncomfortable" is that I have found, in my final two years at this school, a group of students who share my sentimen about the dominant social culture and have created a space and community on the periphery of it. The dominant culture contains traces of high-school-esque social dynamics and antics that I thought we would all have grown out of by the time we got to collge. There is also plenty of sexism, too much drug use, and many other unhealthy things enshrined in the dominant social culture. I say "dominant social culture" because it is the culture that is loudest, most visible, and takes up the most space. I actualy don't think the majority of students affiliate themselves with it, though it is close. This is the culture that has largely replaced and is a surrogate for the frat culture that departed the school in the late nineties. The culture still remains. I don' think it has even attenuated much. And it is the source of most unhealthiness on the campus.
